s%20is%20seen%20during%20a%20port%20visit%20in%20Djibouti.%3Cp%3EUS%20Air%20Force%20photo%20by%20Senior%20Airman%20Kristin%20Savage%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cul%3E%3Cli%3EThe%20US%20Navy%20ousted%20the%20commander%20of%20USS%20Hershel%20Williams%20after%20the%20ship%20ran%20aground%20in%20Africa.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3E%20Capt.%20Lenard%20Mitchell%20was%20relieved%20two%20months%20after%20the%20grounding%20due%20to%20a%C2%A0%26quot%3Bloss%20of%20confidence.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3EMitchell%20is%20the%20ninth%20commanding%20officer%20to%20be%20fired%20that%20the%20Navy%20has%20publicly%20acknowledged.%3C%2Fli%3E%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.military.com%2Fnavy%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3ENavy%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20has%20relieved%20the%20commanding%20officer%20of%20the%20expeditionary%20mobile%20base%20ship%20USS%20Hershel%20%26quot%3BWoody%26quot%3B%20Williams%20two%20months%20after%20the%20vessel%20briefly%20ran%20aground%20outside%20the%20African%20country%20of%20Gabon%2C%20a%20Navy%20statement%20announced%20Monday.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ECapt.%20Lenard%20Mitchell%2C%20the%20commander%20of%20the%20Williams'%20%26quot%3BGold%26quot%3B%20crew%2C%20was%20relieved%20by%20Vice%20Adm.%20Thomas%20Ishee%2C%20the%20commander%20of%20the%20US%206th%20Fleet%2C%20%26quot%3Bdue%20to%20a%20loss%20of%20confidence%20in%20his%20ability%20to%20command.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20Navy's%20statement%20added%20that%20%26quot%3Bthe%20relief%20occurred%20as%20a%20result%20of%20an%20investigation%20into%20the%20soft%20grounding%26quot%3B%20of%20the%20Williams%20near%20the%20port%20of%20Libreville%2C%20Gabon%2C%20on%20May%209%20and%2C%20%26quot%3Bwhile%20the%20investigation%20is%20still%20open%2C%20sufficient%20findings%20of%20fact%20emerged%20during%20the%20investigation%20to%20warrant%20the%20relief%20of%20the%20commanding%20officer.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3ETypically%2C%20the%20Navy%20is%20quick%20to%20remove%20a%20ship's%20commander%20after%20a%20grounding%20%E2%80%94%20usually%20moving%20within%20days%20or%2C%20at%20most%2C%20a%20week%20or%20two.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20the%20cruiser%20USS%20Port%20Royal%20ran%20aground%20on%20a%20shoal%20off%20the%20coast%20of%20Honolulu%20in%202009%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nbcnews.com%2Fid%2Fwbna29104705%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3Ethe%20Navy%20waited%20around%20four%20days%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20%E2%80%94%20until%20the%20ship%20was%20free%20%E2%80%94%20to%20relieve%20its%20commander.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22The%20guided-missile%20destroyer%20USS%20Howard%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F668da2cb3598be27b3453aa4%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22714%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20guided-missile%20destroyer%20USS%20Howard%20transits%20the%20Pacific%20Ocean.%3Cp%3EUS%20Navy%20photo%20by%20Petty%20Officer%203rd%20Class%20Shawn%20J.%20Stewart%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20the%20USS%20Howard%20suffered%20a%20soft%20grounding%20near%20the%20Indonesian%20island%20of%20Bali%20on%20August%2010%2C%202023%2C%20the%20Navy%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.military.com%2Fdaily-news%2F2023%2F08%2F21%2Fnavy-relieves-skipper-of-japan-based-destroyer-uss-howard.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3Erelieved%20its%20skipper%2C%20Cmdr.%20Kenji%20Igawa%2C%20just%20nine%20days%20later%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%202014%2C%20the%20Navy%20took%20about%20two%20weeks%20to%20fire%20the%20commander%20of%20a%20frigate%20%E2%80%94%20the%20USS%20Taylor%20%E2%80%94%20that%20ran%20aground%20in%20the%20Black%20Sea.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22http%3A%2F%2FMilitary.com%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EMilitary.com%3C%2Fa%3E%20asked%20Navy%20officials%20in%20the%20weeks%20after%20the%20Williams'%20grounding%20why%20Mitchell%20had%20not%20been%20relieved%2C%20n